sentences: Sonya Monosoff (born June 11, 1927 in Cleveland, Ohio) is a violinist, a pioneer of the Baroque violin and one of the first American performers to use the Baroque violin in performance.
In 1963 she founded and directed her own ensemble, first called the Baroque Players of New York (later the Chamber Players), performing a range of works from Henry Purcell to Bulent Ariel.
She was the first modern performer to record the Rosary Sonatas and the 8 Sonatas of 1681 by Heinrich Biber.
Her recording of the Bach sonatas with harpsichordist James Weaver won best recording of the year (1963) from Sound_&_Vision_(magazine).

From 1972 to 1997 she taught at Cornell University.
In 1974 she formed the Trio Amade (1974-1997) with fortepianist Malcolm Bilson and cellist John Hsu.

After 1991 she taught violin and chamber music and gave concerts outside the United States, including the Czech Republic and where she was at the Prague Spring International Music Festival in 1993.

Monosoff's discography is currently lacking in CD format reissues, though LP and tape cassette formats are available at many university libraries.

For example, her performance on October 7, 1962 of J.S. Bach's trio sonatas, BWV 1038 and 1079, and her October 29, 1974 performance of Charles Ives' Dialogues for violin and piano (1958) are both available in Cornell's archives.
